b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p4_conversions_multi_step"\n    xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\n    xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"\n    xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Mole Conversions: Multi-step</title>\n        <objref idref="convert_moles"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <section id="p4_conversions_multi_step_DE1">\n          <title></title>\n          <body>  <p>Given the conversion factors between moles and mass and between moles and particles, we\n            can make conversions between mass and particles. We first convert the given value to\n            moles and then convert from moles to the desired value.</p>\n\n        <image src="../webcontent/conversion_factors.png"\n            alt="Converting mass to moles divide by the molar mass. Converting moles to particles\n            multiply by Avogadro\'s number. Converting particles to moles divide by Avogadro\'s number.\n            Converting moles to mass multiply by the molar mass."/></body></section>\n\n        <example id="p4_conversions_multi_step_EX1">\n            <p>A packet of an artificial sweetener contains 40.0 mg of saccharin\n                (C<sub>7</sub>H<sub>5</sub>NO<sub>3</sub>S), which has the structural formula:</p>\n\n            <image src="../webcontent/sweetner.png" style="block" alt="A diagram of a molecule is shown that is made up of two ring structures attached together. The left ring is hexagonal in shape with C atoms at each point of the ring and alternating single and double bonds. A double bond occurs between the C atom at the top vertex of the hexagon and the C atom down and to the left of it. The C atoms on the left, top, and bottom of the structure form a single bond to an H atom each. The two right C atoms make up one side of a pentagon and the other points of the pentagon are made up of a C atom, an N atom, and an S atom if read clockwise. The C atom forms a double bond with an O atom. The N atom forms a single bond with an H atom. The S atom forms two double bonds to two O atoms."/>\n\n            <p>How many saccharin molecules are in a 40.0\xe2\x88\x92mg (0.0400\xe2\x88\x92g) sample of saccharin? </p>\n\n            <p>The number of molecules in a given mass of compound is computed by first deriving the\n                number of moles, and then converting from mol to molecules using Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s number,\n                as illustrated in the diagram below.</p>\n            <image src="../webcontent/mass%20to%20moles.png"\n                alt="A diagram of three boxes connected by a right-facing arrow in between each is shown. The box on the left contains the phrase, \xe2\x80\x9cMass of C subscript seven H subscript five N O subscript three S ( g ),\xe2\x80\x9d the middle box reads, \xe2\x80\x9cMoles of C subscript seven H subscript five N O subscript three S ( mol ),\xe2\x80\x9d while the one on the right contains the phrase, \xe2\x80\x9cNumber of C subscript seven H subscript five N O subscript three S molecules.\xe2\x80\x9d There is a phrase under the left arrow that says, \xe2\x80\x9cDivide by molar mass (g / mol),\xe2\x80\x9d and under the right arrow it states, \xe2\x80\x9cMultiply by Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s number ( mol superscript negative one).\xe2\x80\x9d"/>\n            \n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}0.0400\\;\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S}\\;\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S}}{183.18\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S}}\\;\\;\\;\\times\\frac{6.022\\times10^{23}\\;\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S}}\\;\\;=\\;1.31\\times10^{20}\\;\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm C}_7{\\mathrm H}_5{\\mathrm{NO}}_3\\mathrm S$$</formula>\n\n          \n        </example>\n\n        <example id="p4_conversions_multi_step_EX2">\n            <p>An average banana contains 1.4&times;10<sup>22</sup> molecules of glucose,\n                    C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>12</sub>O<sub>6</sub> . What is this quantity in grams?</p>\n\n            <p>The mass of a given number of molecules of compound is computed by first deriving the\n                number of moles, and then converting from mol to grams using the molar mass, as\n                illustrated in the diagram below.</p>\n\n            <image src="../webcontent/molecules-moles.png"\n                alt="Converting molecules to moles divide by Avogadro\'s number. Converting moles \n                to mass multiply by the molar mass."/>\n            \n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}1.4\\times10^{22}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6}\\;\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6}}{6.022\\times10^{23}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6}}\\;\\;\\;\\times\\;\\frac{180.18\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6}}\\;\\;=\\;4.2\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_6{\\mathrm H}_{12}{\\mathrm O}_6$$</formula>\n\n         \n        </example>\n        \n      <!--  <section>\n            <title>Interactive Example</title>\n            <body><iframe src="https://h5p.org/h5p/embed/220777" width="750" height="440"></iframe></body>\n        </section>-->\n        \n        <section>\n            <title>Interactive Example </title>\n            <body>\n                <p><em style="italic">Click "NEXT" to see the example progress.</em></p>\n                <wb:inline idref="convert2atoms_ie"></wb:inline>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        \n        <youtube src="X7AnxofHIe4" id="p4_conversions_multi_step_V1"></youtube>\n        <wb:inline idref="helium_conversion_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="multi_mole_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="multi_mole_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'